SIMPLE: intermeddle
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Intermeddle
<hw>In`ter*med"dle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>entremedlen</ets>, <ets>entermellen</ets>, to mix together, OF.
<ets>entremedler</ets>, <ets>entremeller</ets>, <ets>entremesler</ets>,
F. <ets>entrem⟦ecir⟧ler</ets>. See <er>Inter-</er>, and
<er>Meddle</er>.]</ety> <def>To meddle with the affairs of others; to
meddle officiously; to interpose or interfere improperly; to mix or
meddle with.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The practice of Spain hath been, by war and by conditions of
treaty, to <qex>intermeddle</qex> with foreign states.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To interpose; interfere. See
<er>Interpose</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Intermeddle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Intermeddle
<hw>In`ter*med"dle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To intermix;
to mingle.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Many other adventures are <qex>intermeddled</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Intermeddler</ent>⟦br⟧
